subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Males are immediately identifiable by the apically truncate medial projection on T7 (
Fig. 60A
) and the absence of setae in the wing’s first submarginal cell. Males may be otherwise determined by the following character combination: mandible with inferior tooth large, vaguely triangular, but only weakly angled off main blade if at all (
Fig. 50A
); scape without maculation; scutum shiny, with no or insignificant impunctate areas; T1– T6 with thin apical appressed setal bands; and T6 usually with slightly pointed lateral projections directed posteriorly off the gradulus. Females may be determined by the following character combination: clypeus unusually flat, not half-circular in ventral view (
Fig. 40A
); scutum shiny, with no or insignificant impunctate areas; basitibial plate with distal edge straight or nearly so; T1–T4 with apical appressed setal bands; and anal fimbria dark, black to brown.

Male description.
Head: Facial maculations pale to richly yellow, sometimes yellow-green. Galea reaching or slightly passing edge of foretrochanter in repose; light to dark brown; smooth to weakly tessellate, usually with strong reflections. Mandible with inferior tooth ovular to weakly triangular, running roughly parallel to main blade; maculated from base to near start of inferior tooth (
Fig. 50A
). Labral rim tridentate. Clypeal maculation a low band, sometimes near absent, reaching sides or not, always filling less than half of clypeal height, usually much less than a third (
Fig. 50A
); punctation significantly sparser within maculation than without. Paraocular area immaculate. Supraclypeal area immaculate. Scape immaculate. Mesosoma: Scutum shiny; with minute impunctate areas. Tegula somewhat transparent to translucent, tan to medium brown. Basitibial plate present; strong. Metasoma: T1 sometimes with appressed setae throughout, more often with apical appressed setal band; T2–T5 with thinner apical appressed setal bands, usually weakly or not undulate. Terga moderately to weakly tessellate between punctures, with some weak to moderate reflections; not often apparent through appressed setae. Tergal rims transparent, clear to light brown. Male T7 (
Fig. 60A
) unusual: lateral projections strongly recurved, sharp; medial projections apparently fused into single, apically truncated point. Male S5 (
Figs. 38A, 38C
) setal arrangement unremarkable, without large, distinctive patches, at most longer along rim. Male S6 (
Fig. 38A
) clearly medially emarginate. Male S7 (
Fig. 65A
) with setae absent or nearly so around midpoint of length; widening from midpoint to tip, apical half widest near rounded lateral tips; apical half heart-shaped, rim broadly emarginate between lateral tips. Male S8 (
Fig. 70A
) lateral projections distinct; medial projection widened at tip, apically emarginate. Male genital capsule (
Fig. 75A
) with outer corners, where gonocoxite tips curve inward, marked by obvious flange of about 90 degrees or slightly less, best seen in profile; from corner to apex, in profile, gonocoxite relatively unmodified, concave or straight; tip, in profile, rounded and strongly curved ventrally, with minor dorsal projection obscurely pointed; gonostylus tip position significantly exceeding that of gonocoxite, measured from above along primary axis of latter. Pubescence: See 
Fig. 55A
. Appears dark gray overall, primarily because of dark tergal basal zones. Setae white to off-white, except as follows: vertex and scutum with variable intermix of dark, almost always with some present; leg inner faces with orangish to brown; tergal basal zones dark.

Female
similar to male, except: Head: Mandible with inferior tooth large, ridge-like, moderately angled off main blade (
Fig. 40A
). Labral rim rounded; fully maculated. Clypeal maculation a band of highly variable size, reaching lateral sides, typically filling slightly over half of clypeal height medially (
Fig. 40A
). Supraclypeal area rarely maculated; small dot, if present. Mesosoma: Scutum impunctate areas less common. Midtibial spur apically curved; tan to orange. Basitibial plate flattened distally, otherwise teardropped overall (
Fig. 45A
). Metasoma: T1 with appressed setae throughout; T2–T4 with appressed setal bands of variable width, thin to nearly filling tergal length, usually undulate; T5 with variable amounts appressed setae, usually covered and never absent. T4 impunctate rim of short length medially, often barely visible. Anal fimbria strongly triangular, covering third to half of T5 length medially. Pubescence: See 
Fig. 45A
. Hindbasitarsal brush light to dark brown; T1 sometimes with appressed setae darkened; anal fimbria medium brown to blackish, sometimes with light around perimeter.

